# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bot-management
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bot-management/botnet] A **botnet** is a group of Internet-connected devices, each of which runs one or more bots.
[src:bot-management/botnet] Botnets can be used to perform distributed denial-of-service (DDoS) attacks, steal data, send spam, and allow the attacker to access the device and its connection.
[src:bot-management/botnet] The owner can control the botnet using command and control (C&C) software.
[src:bot-management/botnet] The word "botnet" is a portmanteau of the words "robot" and "network".
[src:bot-management/botnet] The term is usually used with a negative or malicious connotation.
[src:bot-management/botnet] A botnet is a logical collection of Internet-connected devices, such as computers, smartphones or Internet of things (IoT) devices whose security have been breached and control ceded to a third party.
[src:bot-management/botnet] Each compromised device, known as a "bot," is created when a device is penetrated by software from a *malware* (malicious software) distribution.
[src:bot-management/botnet] The controller of a botnet can direct the activities of these compromised computers through communication channels formed by network protocols, such as Internet Relay Chat (IRC) and Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP).
[src:bot-management/botnet] Operating, building, or using a botnet to access or control devices without their owners’ authorization is illegal in most jurisdictions and is regularly prosecuted as hacking, fraud, or related cyber-crime.
[src:bot-management/botnet] Law enforcement and private parties also use legal tools to disrupt botnets, but those takedowns raise separate legal and constitutional issues.
[src:bot-management/botnet] Botnets are increasingly rented out by cyber criminals as commodities for a variety of purposes, including as booter/stresser services.
[src:bot-management/botnet] Botnet architecture has evolved over time in an effort to evade detection and disruption.
[src:bot-management/botnet] Traditionally, bot programs are constructed as clients which communicate via existing servers.
[src:bot-management/botnet] This allows the **bot herder** (the controller of the botnet) to perform all control from a remote location, which obfuscates the traffic.
[src:bot-management/botnet] Many recent botnets now rely on existing peer-to-peer networks to communicate.
[src:bot-management/botnet] These P2P bot programs perform the same actions as the client–server model, but they do not require a central server to communicate.
[src:bot-management/botnet] The first botnets on the Internet used a client–server model to accomplish their tasks.
[src:bot-management/botnet] Typically, these botnets operate through Internet Relay Chat networks, domains, or websites.
[src:bot-management/botnet] Infected clients access a predetermined location and await incoming commands from the server.
[src:bot-management/botnet] The bot herder sends commands to the server, which relays them to the clients.
[src:bot-management/botnet] Clients execute the commands and report their results back to the bot herder.
[src:bot-management/botnet] In the case of IRC botnets, infected clients connect to an infected IRC server and join a channel pre-designated for C&C by the bot herder.
[src:bot-management/botnet] The bot herder sends commands to the channel via the IRC server.
[src:bot-management/botnet] Each client retrieves the commands and executes them.
[src:bot-management/botnet] Clients send messages back to the IRC channel with the results of their actions.
[src:bot-management/botnet] In response to efforts to detect and decapitate IRC botnets, bot herders have begun deploying malware on peer-to-peer networks.
[src:bot-management/botnet] These bots may use digital signatures so that only someone with access to the private key can control the botnet, such as in Gameover ZeuS and the ZeroAccess botnet.
[src:bot-management/botnet] Newer botnets fully operate over P2P networks.
[src:bot-management/botnet] Rather than communicate with a centralized server, P2P bots perform as both a command distribution server and a client that receives commands.
[src:bot-management/botnet] This avoids having any single point of failure, which is an issue for centralized botnets.
[src:bot-management/botnet] In order to find other infected machines, P2P bots discreetly probe random IP addresses until they identify another infected machine.
[src:bot-management/botnet] The contacted bot replies with information such as its software version and list of known bots.
[src:bot-management/botnet] If one of the bots' version is lower than the other, they will initiate a file transfer to update.
[src:bot-management/botnet] This way, each bot grows its list of infected machines and updates itself by periodically communicating to all known bots.
[src:bot-management/botnet] A botnet's originator (known as a "bot herder" or "bot master") controls the botnet remotely.
[src:bot-management/botnet] This is known as the command-and-control (C&C).
[src:bot-management/botnet] The program for the operation must communicate via a covert channel to the client on the victim's machine (zombie computer).
[src:bot-management/botnet] IRC is a historically favored means of C&C because of its communication protocol.
[src:bot-management/botnet] A bot herder creates an IRC channel for infected clients to join.
[src:bot-management/botnet] Messages sent to the channel are broadcast to all channel members.
[src:bot-management/botnet] The bot herder may set the channel's topic to command the botnet.
[src:bot-management/botnet] For example, the message `:herder!herder@example.com TOPIC #channel DDoS www.victim.com` from the bot herder alerts all infected clients belonging to #channel to begin a DDoS attack on the website www.victim.com.
[src:bot-management/botnet] An example response `:bot1!bot1@compromised.net PRIVMSG #channel I am DDoSing www.victim.com` by a bot client alerts the bot herder that it has begun the attack.
[src:bot-management/botnet] Some botnets implement custom versions of well-known protocols.
[src:bot-management/botnet] The implementation differences can be used for detection of botnets.
[src:bot-management/botnet] For example, Mega-D features a slightly modified Simple Mail Transfer Protocol (SMTP) implementation for testing spam capability.
[src:bot-management/botnet] Bringing down the Mega-D's SMTP server disables the entire pool of bots that rely upon the same SMTP server.
[src:bot-management/botnet] In computer science, a zombie computer is a computer connected to the Internet that has been compromised by a hacker, computer virus or trojan horse and can be used to perform malicious tasks under remote direction.
[src:bot-management/botnet] Botnets of zombie computers are often used to spread e-mail spam and launch denial-of-service attacks (DDoS).
[src:bot-management/botnet] Most owners of zombie computers are unaware that their system is being used in this way.
[src:bot-management/botnet] Because the owner tends to be unaware, these computers are metaphorically compared to zombies.
[src:bot-management/botnet] A coordinated DDoS attack by multiple botnet machines also resembles a zombie horde attack.
[src:bot-management/botnet] The process of stealing computing resources as a result of a system being joined to a "botnet" is sometimes referred to as "scrumping".
[src:bot-management/botnet] Botnet command and control (C&C) protocols have been implemented in a number of ways, from traditional IRC approaches to more sophisticated versions.
[src:bot-management/botnet] Telnet botnets use a simple C&C botnet protocol in which bots connect to the main command server to host the botnet.
[src:bot-management/botnet] Bots are added to the botnet by using a scanning script, which runs on an external server and scans IP ranges for telnet and SSH server default logins.
[src:bot-management/botnet] Once a login is found, the scanning server can infect it through SSH with malware, which pings the control server.
[src:bot-management/botnet] IRC networks use simple, low-bandwidth communication methods, making them widely used to host botnets.
[src:bot-management/botnet] They tend to be relatively simple in construction and have been used with moderate success for coordinating DDoS attacks and spam campaigns while being able to continually switch channels to avoid being taken down.
[src:bot-management/botnet] However, in some cases, merely blocking certain keywords has proven effective in stopping IRC-based botnets.
[src:bot-management/botnet] The RFC 1459 (IRC) standard is popular with botnets.
[src:bot-management/botnet] The first known popular botnet controller script, "MaXiTE Bot" used the IRC XDCC protocol for private control commands.
[src:bot-management/botnet] One problem with using IRC is that each bot client must know the IRC server, port, and channel to be of any use to the botnet.
[src:bot-management/botnet] Anti-malware organizations can detect and shut down these servers and channels, effectively halting the botnet attack.
[src:bot-management/botnet] If this happens, clients are still infected, but they typically lie dormant since they have no way of receiving instructions.
[src:bot-management/botnet] To mitigate this problem, a botnet can consist of several servers or channels.
[src:bot-management/botnet] If one of the servers or channels becomes disabled, the botnet simply switches to another.
[src:bot-management/botnet] It is still possible to detect and disrupt additional botnet servers or channels by sniffing IRC traffic.
[src:bot-management/botnet] A botnet adversary can even potentially gain knowledge of the control scheme and imitate the bot herder by issuing commands correctly.
[src:bot-management/botnet] Since most botnets using IRC networks and domains can be taken down over time, hackers have moved to P2P botnets with C&C to make the botnet more resilient and resistant to termination.
[src:bot-management/botnet] Some have also used encryption as a way to secure or lock down the botnet from others; most of the time when they use encryption it is public-key cryptography and has presented challenges in both implementing it and breaking it.
[src:bot-management/botnet] Many large botnets tend to use domains rather than IRC in their construction (see Rustock botnet and Srizbi botnet).
[src:bot-management/botnet] They are usually hosted with bulletproof hosting services.
[src:bot-management/botnet] This is one of the earliest types of C&C.
[src:bot-management/botnet] A zombie computer accesses a specially designed webpage or domain(s) which serves the list of controlling commands.
[src:bot-management/botnet] The advantages of using web pages or domains as C&C is that a large botnet can be effectively controlled and maintained with very simple code that can be readily updated.
[src:bot-management/botnet] Disadvantages of using this method are that it uses a considerable amount of bandwidth at large scale, and domains can be quickly seized by government agencies with little effort.
[src:bot-management/botnet] If the domains controlling the botnets are not seized, they are also easy targets to compromise with denial-of-service attacks.
[src:bot-management/botnet] Fast-flux DNS can be used to make it difficult to track down the control servers, which may change from day to day.
[src:bot-management/botnet] Control servers may also hop from DNS domain to DNS domain, with domain generation algorithms being used to create new DNS names for controller servers.
[src:bot-management/botnet] Some botnets use free DNS hosting services such as DynDns.org, No-IP.com, and Afraid.org to point a subdomain towards an IRC server that harbors the bots.
[src:bot-management/botnet] While these free DNS services do not themselves host attacks, they provide reference points (often hard-coded into the botnet executable).
[src:bot-management/botnet] Removing such services can cripple an entire botnet.
[src:bot-management/botnet] Calling back to popular sites such as GitHub, Twitter, Reddit, Instagram, the XMPP open source instant message protocol and Tor hidden services are popular ways of avoiding egress filtering to communicate with a C&C server.
[src:bot-management/botnet] This example illustrates how a botnet is created and used for malicious gain.
[src:bot-management/botnet] The *bot* instructs the infected PC to connect to a particular command-and-control (C&C) server.
[src:bot-management/botnet] The botmaster may then use the bots to gather keystrokes or use form grabbing to steal online credentials and may rent out the botnet as DDoS and/or spam as a service or sell the credentials online for a profit.
[src:bot-management/botnet] Depending on the quality and capability of the bots, the value is increased or decreased.
[src:bot-management/botnet] Newer bots can automatically scan their environment and propagate themselves using vulnerabilities and weak passwords.
[src:bot-management/botnet] Generally, the more vulnerabilities a bot can scan and propagate through, the more valuable it becomes to a botnet controller community.
[src:bot-management/botnet] Computers can be co-opted into a botnet when they execute malicious software.
[src:bot-management/botnet] This can be accomplished by luring users into making a drive-by download, exploiting web browser vulnerabilities, or by tricking the user into running a Trojan horse program, which may come from an email attachment.
[src:bot-management/botnet] This malware will typically install modules that allow the computer to be commanded and controlled by the botnet's operator.
[src:bot-management/botnet] After the software is downloaded, it will call home (send a reconnection packet) to the host computer.
[src:bot-management/botnet] When the reconnection is made, depending on how it is written, a Trojan may then delete itself or may remain present to update and maintain the modules.
[src:bot-management/botnet] In some cases, a botnet may be temporarily created by volunteer hacktivists, such as with implementations of the Low Orbit Ion Cannon as used by 4chan members during Project Chanology in 2010.
[src:bot-management/botnet] China's Great Cannon of China allows the modification of legitimate web browsing traffic at internet backbones into China to create a large ephemeral botnet to attack large targets such as GitHub in 2015.
[src:bot-management/botnet] Beginning in July 2009, similar botnet capabilities have also emerged for the growing smartphone market.
[src:bot-management/botnet] Examples include the July 2009 in the "wild" release of the Sexy Space text message worm, the world's first botnet capable SMS worm, which targeted the Symbian operating system in Nokia smartphones.
[src:bot-management/botnet] Later that month, researcher Charlie Miller revealed a proof of concept text message worm for the iPhone at Black Hat Briefings.
[src:bot-management/botnet] Also in July, United Arab Emirates consumers were targeted by the Etisalat BlackBerry spyware program.
[src:bot-management/botnet] In the 2010s, the security community is divided as to the real-world potential of mobile botnets.
[src:bot-management/botnet] The botnet controller community constantly competes over who has the most bots, the highest overall bandwidth, and the most "high-quality" infected machines, like university, corporate, and even governmental machines.
[src:bot-management/botnet] While botnets are often named after the malware that created them, multiple botnets typically use the same malware but are operated by different entities.
[src:bot-management/botnet] Botnets can be used for many electronic scams.
[src:bot-management/botnet] These botnets can be used to distribute malware such as viruses to take control of a regular user's computer/software.
[src:bot-management/botnet] By taking control of someone's personal computer they have unlimited access to their personal information, including passwords and login information to accounts.
[src:bot-management/botnet] Phishing is the acquiring of login information to the "victim's" accounts with a link the "victim" clicks on that is sent through an email or text.
[src:bot-management/botnet] A survey by Verizon found that around two-thirds of electronic "espionage" cases come from phishing.
[src:bot-management/botnet] The geographic dispersal of botnets means that each recruit must be individually identified/corralled/repaired and limits the benefits of filtering.
[src:bot-management/botnet] Norton AntiBot was aimed at consumers, but most target enterprises and/or ISPs.
[src:bot-management/botnet] Host-based techniques use heuristics to identify bot behavior that has bypassed conventional anti-virus software.
[src:bot-management/botnet] Network-based approaches tend to use the techniques described above; shutting down C&C servers, null-routing DNS entries, or completely shutting down IRC servers.
[src:bot-management/botnet] BotHunter is software, developed with support from the U.S.
[src:bot-management/botnet] Army Research Office, that detects botnet activity within a network by analyzing network traffic and comparing it to patterns characteristic of malicious processes.
[src:bot-management/botnet] Detecting automated bot becomes more difficult as newer and more sophisticated generations of bots get launched by attackers.
[src:bot-management/botnet] For example, an automated attack can deploy a large bot army and apply brute-force methods with highly accurate username and password lists to hack into accounts.
[src:bot-management/botnet] The idea is to overwhelm sites with tens of thousands of requests from different IPs all over the world, but with each bot only submitting a single request every 10 minutes or so, which can result in more than 5 million attempts per day.
[src:bot-management/botnet] In these cases, many tools try to leverage volumetric detection, but automated bot attacks now have ways of circumventing triggers of volumetric detection.
[src:bot-management/botnet] One of the techniques for detecting these bot attacks is what's known as "signature-based systems" in which the software will attempt to detect patterns in the request packet.
[src:bot-management/botnet] However, attacks are constantly evolving, so this may not be a viable option when patterns cannot be discerned from thousands of requests.
[src:bot-management/botnet] There is also the behavioral approach to thwarting bots, which ultimately tries to distinguish bots from humans.
[src:bot-management/botnet] By identifying non-human behavior and recognizing known bot behavior, this process can be applied at the user, browser, and network levels.
[src:bot-management/botnet] The most capable method of using software to combat a virus has been to utilize honeypot software in order to convince the malware that a system is vulnerable.
[src:bot-management/botnet] The malicious files are then analyzed using forensic software.
[src:bot-management/botnet] On 15 July 2014, the Subcommittee on Crime and Terrorism of the Committee on the Judiciary, United States Senate, held a hearing on the threats posed by botnets and the public and private efforts to disrupt and dismantle them.
[src:bot-management/botnet] The rise in vulnerable IoT devices has led to an increase in IoT-based botnet attacks.
[src:bot-management/botnet] To address this, a novel network-based anomaly detection method for IoT called N-BaIoT was introduced.
[src:bot-management/botnet] It captures network behavior snapshots and employs deep autoencoders to identify abnormal traffic from compromised IoT devices.
[src:bot-management/botnet] The method was tested by infecting nine IoT devices with Mirai and BASHLITE botnets, showing its ability to accurately and promptly detect attacks originating from compromised IoT devices within a botnet.
[src:bot-management/botnet] Additionally, comparing different ways of detecting botnets is really useful for researchers.
[src:bot-management/botnet] It helps them see how well each method works compared to others.
[src:bot-management/botnet] This kind of comparison is good because it lets researchers evaluate the methods fairly and find ways to make them better.
[src:bot-management/botnet] The first botnet was first acknowledged and exposed by EarthLink during a lawsuit with notorious spammer Khan C.
[src:bot-management/botnet] The botnet was constructed for the purpose of bulk spam, and accounted for nearly 25% of all spam at the time.
[src:bot-management/botnet] Around 2006, to thwart detection, some botnets were scaling back in size.
[src:bot-management/botnet] The following is a non-exhaustive list of some historical botnets.
[src:bot-management/captcha] A **CAPTCHA** (/ˈkæp.tʃə/ *KAP-chə*) is a type of challenge–response Turing test used in computing to determine whether the user is human in order to deter bot attacks and spam.
[src:bot-management/captcha] The term was coined in 2003 by Luis von Ahn, Manuel Blum, Nicholas J.
[src:bot-management/captcha] It is a contrived acronym for "**Completely Automated Public Turing test to tell Computers and Humans Apart**".
[src:bot-management/captcha] A historically common type of CAPTCHA (displayed as reCAPTCHA v1) was first invented in 1997 by two groups working in parallel.
[src:bot-management/captcha] This form of CAPTCHA requires entering a sequence of letters or numbers from a distorted image.
[src:bot-management/captcha] Because the test is administered by a computer, in contrast to the standard Turing test that is administered by a human, CAPTCHAs are sometimes described as reverse Turing tests.
[src:bot-management/captcha] Two widely used CAPTCHA services are Google's reCAPTCHA and the independent hCaptcha.
[src:bot-management/captcha] It takes the average person approximately 10 seconds to solve a typical CAPTCHA.
[src:bot-management/captcha] The purpose of CAPTCHAs is to prevent spam on websites, such as promotion spam, registration spam, and data scraping.
[src:bot-management/captcha] Many websites use CAPTCHA effectively to prevent bot raiding.
[src:bot-management/captcha] CAPTCHAs are designed so that humans can complete them, while most robots cannot.
[src:bot-management/captcha] Newer CAPTCHAs look at the user's behaviour on the internet, to prove that they are a human.
[src:bot-management/captcha] A normal CAPTCHA test only appears if the user acts like a bot, such as when they request webpages, or click links too fast.
[src:bot-management/captcha] Since the 1980s–1990s, users have wanted to make text illegible to computers.
[src:bot-management/captcha] The first such people were hackers, posting about sensitive topics to Internet forums they thought were being automatically monitored on keywords.
[src:bot-management/captcha] To circumvent such filters, they replaced a word with look-alike characters.
[src:bot-management/captcha] *HELLO* could become `|-|3|_|_()` or `)-(3££0`, and others, such that a filter could not detect *all* of them.
[src:bot-management/captcha] One of the earliest commercial uses of CAPTCHAs was in the Gausebeck–Levchin test.
[src:bot-management/captcha] In 2000, idrive.com began to protect its signup page with a CAPTCHA and prepared to file a patent.
[src:bot-management/captcha] In 2001, PayPal used such tests as part of a fraud prevention strategy in which they asked humans to "retype distorted text that programs have difficulty recognizing".
[src:bot-management/captcha] PayPal co founder and CTO Max Levchin helped commercialize this use.
[src:bot-management/captcha] AltaVista implemented an early CAPTCHA scheme to protect against fraudulent account registrations.
[src:bot-management/captcha] A popular deployment of CAPTCHA technology, reCAPTCHA, was acquired by Google in 2009.
[src:bot-management/captcha] In addition to preventing bot fraud for its users, Google used reCAPTCHA and CAPTCHA technology to digitize the archives of *The New York Times* and books from Google Books in 2011.
[src:bot-management/captcha] With the rising application of AI making it feasible to defeat the tests and the appearance of scams disguised as CAPTCHAs, their use risks being outmoded.
[src:bot-management/captcha] CAPTCHAs are automated, requiring little human maintenance or intervention to administer, producing benefits in cost and reliability.
[src:bot-management/captcha] Modern text-based CAPTCHAs are designed such that they require the simultaneous use of three separate abilities—invariant recognition, segmentation, and parsing to complete the task.
[src:bot-management/captcha] Each of these problems poses a significant challenge for a computer, even in isolation.
[src:bot-management/captcha] Therefore, these three techniques in tandem make CAPTCHAs difficult for computers to solve.
[src:bot-management/captcha] Whilst primarily used for security reasons, CAPTCHAs can also serve as a benchmark task for artificial intelligence technologies.
[src:bot-management/captcha] According to an article by Ahn, Blum and Langford, "any program that passes the tests generated by a CAPTCHA can be used to solve a hard unsolved AI problem".
[src:bot-management/captcha] They argue that the advantages of using hard AI problems as a means for security are twofold.
[src:bot-management/captcha] Either the problem goes unsolved and there remains a reliable method for distinguishing humans from computers, or the problem is solved and a difficult AI problem is resolved along with it.
[src:bot-management/captcha] CAPTCHAs based on reading text—or other visual-perception tasks—prevent blind or visually impaired users from accessing the protected resource.
[src:bot-management/captcha] Because CAPTCHAs are designed to be unreadable by machines, common assistive technology tools such as screen readers cannot interpret them.
[src:bot-management/captcha] The use of CAPTCHA thus excludes a small percentage of users from using significant subsets of such common Web-based services as PayPal, Gmail, Orkut, Yahoo!, many forum and weblog systems, etc.
[src:bot-management/captcha] In certain jurisdictions, site owners could become targets of litigation if they are using CAPTCHAs that discriminate against certain people with disabilities.
[src:bot-management/captcha] For example, a CAPTCHA may make a site incompatible with Section 508 in the United States.
[src:bot-management/captcha] Any hard artificial intelligence problem, such as speech recognition, can be used as CAPTCHA.
[src:bot-management/captcha] Some implementations of CAPTCHAs permit users to opt for an audio CAPTCHA, such as reCAPTCHA, though a 2011 paper demonstrated a technique for defeating the popular schemes at the time.
[src:bot-management/captcha] A method of improving CAPTCHA to ease the work with it was proposed by ProtectWebForm and named "Smart CAPTCHA".
[src:bot-management/captcha] Developers are advised to combine CAPTCHA with JavaScript.
[src:bot-management/captcha] Since it is hard for most bots to parse and execute JavaScript, a combinatory method which fills the CAPTCHA fields and hides both the image and the field from human eyes was proposed.
[src:bot-management/captcha] One alternative method involves displaying to the user a simple mathematical equation and requiring the user to enter the solution as verification.
[src:bot-management/captcha] Although these are much easier to defeat using software, they are suitable for scenarios where graphical imagery is not appropriate, and they provide a much higher level of accessibility for blind users than the image-based CAPTCHAs.
[src:bot-management/captcha] These are sometimes referred to as MAPTCHAs (M = "mathematical").
[src:bot-management/captcha] However, these may be difficult for users with a cognitive disorder, such as dyscalculia.
[src:bot-management/captcha] Challenges such as a logic puzzle, or trivia question can also be used as a CAPTCHA.
[src:bot-management/captcha] There is research into their resistance against countermeasures.
[src:bot-management/captcha] Two main ways to bypass CAPTCHA include using cheap human labor to recognize them, and using machine learning to build an automated solver.
[src:bot-management/captcha] According to former Google "click fraud czar" Shuman Ghosemajumder, there are numerous services which solve CAPTCHAs automatically.
[src:bot-management/captcha] There was not a systematic methodology for designing or evaluating early CAPTCHAs.
[src:bot-management/captcha] As a result, there were many instances in which CAPTCHAs were of a fixed length and therefore automated tasks could be constructed to successfully make educated guesses about where segmentation should take place.
[src:bot-management/captcha] Other early CAPTCHAs contained limited sets of words, which made the test much easier to game.
[src:bot-management/captcha] Still others made the mistake of relying too heavily on background confusion in the image.
[src:bot-management/captcha] In each case, algorithms were created that were successfully able to complete the task by exploiting these design flaws.
[src:bot-management/captcha] However, light changes to the CAPTCHA could thwart them.
[src:bot-management/captcha] Modern CAPTCHAs like reCAPTCHA rely on present variations of characters that are collapsed together, making them hard to segment, and they have warded off automated tasks.
[src:bot-management/captcha] In October 2013, artificial intelligence company Vicarious claimed that it had developed a generic CAPTCHA-solving algorithm that was able to solve modern CAPTCHAs with character recognition rates of up to 90%.
[src:bot-management/captcha] However, Luis von Ahn, a pioneer of early CAPTCHA and founder of reCAPTCHA, said: "It's hard for me to be impressed since I see these every few months." 50 similar claims to that of Vicarious had been made since 2003.
[src:bot-management/captcha] In August 2014 at Usenix WoOT conference, Bursztein et al. presented the first generic CAPTCHA-solving algorithm based on reinforcement learning and demonstrated its efficiency against many popular CAPTCHA schemas.
[src:bot-management/captcha] In October 2018 at ACM CCS'18 conference, Ye et al. presented a deep learning-based attack that could consistently solve all 11 text captcha schemes used by the top-50 popular websites in 2018.
[src:bot-management/captcha] An effective CAPTCHA solver can be trained using as few as 500 real CAPTCHAs.
[src:bot-management/captcha] It is possible to subvert CAPTCHAs by relaying them to a sweatshop of human operators who are employed to decode CAPTCHAs.
[src:bot-management/captcha] A 2005 paper from a W3C working group said that they could verify hundreds per hour.
[src:bot-management/captcha] In 2010, the University of California at San Diego conducted a large scale study of CAPTCHA farms.
[src:bot-management/captcha] The retail price for solving one million CAPTCHAs was as low as $1,000.
[src:bot-management/captcha] Another technique consists of using a script to re-post the target site's CAPTCHA as a CAPTCHA to the attacker's site, which unsuspecting humans visit and solve within a short while for the script to use.
[src:bot-management/captcha] In 2023, researchers prompted ChatGPT to trick a TaskRabbit worker into solving a CAPTCHA by telling the worker it was not a robot and had impaired vision.
[src:bot-management/captcha] There are multiple Internet companies like *2Captcha* and *DeathByCaptcha* that offer human and machine backed CAPTCHA solving services for as low as US$0.50 per 1000 solved CAPTCHAs.
[src:bot-management/captcha] These services offer APIs and libraries that enable users to integrate CAPTCHA circumvention into the tools that CAPTCHAs were designed to block in the first place.
[src:bot-management/captcha] Howard Yeend has identified two implementation issues with poorly designed CAPTCHA systems: reusing the session ID of a known CAPTCHA image, and CAPTCHAs residing on shared servers.
[src:bot-management/captcha] Sometimes, if part of the software generating the CAPTCHA is client-side (the validation is done on a server but the text that the user is required to identify is rendered on the client side), then users can modify the client to display the un-rendered text.
[src:bot-management/captcha] Some CAPTCHA systems use MD5 hashes stored client-side, which may leave the CAPTCHA vulnerable to a brute-force attack.
[src:bot-management/captcha] Some researchers have proposed alternatives including image recognition CAPTCHAs which require users to identify simple objects in the images presented.
[src:bot-management/captcha] The argument in favor of these schemes is that tasks like object recognition are more complex to perform than text recognition and therefore should be more resilient to machine learning based attacks.
[src:bot-management/captcha] Chew et al. published their work in the 7th International Information Security Conference, ISC'04, proposing three different versions of image recognition CAPTCHAs, and validating the proposal with user studies.
[src:bot-management/captcha] It is suggested that one of the versions, the anomaly CAPTCHA, is best with 100% of human users being able to pass an anomaly CAPTCHA with at least 90% probability in 42 seconds.
[src:bot-management/captcha] Datta et al. published their paper in the ACM Multimedia '05 Conference, named IMAGINATION (IMAge Generation for INternet AuthenticaTION), proposing a systematic way to image recognition CAPTCHAs.
[src:bot-management/captcha] Images are distorted so image recognition approaches cannot recognize them.
[src:bot-management/captcha] Douceur, Jon Howell, and Jared Saul) claim to have developed Animal Species Image Recognition for Restricting Access (ASIRRA) which ask users to distinguish cats from dogs.
[src:bot-management/captcha] Microsoft had a beta version of this for websites to use.
[src:bot-management/captcha] They claim "Asirra is easy for users; it can be solved by humans 99.6% of the time in under 30 seconds.
[src:bot-management/captcha] Anecdotally, users seemed to find the experience of using Asirra much more enjoyable than a text-based CAPTCHA." This solution was described in a 2007 paper to Proceedings of 14th ACM Conference on Computer and Communications Security (CCS).
[src:bot-management/captcha] False CAPTCHAs are being used to deliver malware.
[src:bot-management/captcha] Threat actors take advantage of "verification fatigue" to trick people into copying and executing console commands that download and install malicious code such as spyware in order to steal passwords, mobile wallet details, and other personal information.
[src:bot-management/captcha] Such attempted frauds are reported to succeed more often than others.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] In computing, a **denial-of-service attack** (**DoS attack** /dɒs/ *doss*) is a cyberattack in which the perpetrator seeks to make a machine or network resource unavailable to its intended users by temporarily or indefinitely disrupting services of a host connected to a network.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Denial of service is typically accomplished by flooding the targeted machine or resource with superfluous requests in an attempt to overload systems and prevent some or all legitimate requests from being fulfilled.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] The range of attacks varies widely, spanning from inundating a server with millions of requests to slow its performance, overwhelming a server with a substantial amount of invalid data, to submitting requests with an illegitimate IP address.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] In a **distributed denial-of-service attack** (**DDoS attack** /ˈdiː.dɒs/ *DEE-doss*), the incoming traffic flooding the victim originates from many different sources.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] More sophisticated strategies are required to mitigate this type of attack; simply attempting to block a single source is insufficient.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] A DDoS attack is analogous to a group of people crowding the entry door of a shop, making it hard for legitimate customers to enter, thus disrupting trade and losing the business money.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Criminal perpetrators of DDoS attacks often target sites or services hosted on high-profile web servers such as banks or credit card payment gateways.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Revenge and blackmail, as well as hacktivism, can motivate these attacks.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Panix, the third-oldest Internet service provider (ISP) in the world, was the target of what is thought to be the first DoS attack.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] On September 6, 1996, Panix was subject to a SYN flood attack, which brought down its services for several days while hardware vendors, notably Cisco, figured out a proper defense.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] The release of sample code during the event led to the online attack of Sprint, EarthLink, E-Trade, and other major corporations in the year to follow.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] In February 2020, Amazon Web Services experienced an attack with a peak volume of 2.3 Tb/s.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] In July 2021, Cloudflare boasted of protecting its client from a DDoS attack from a global Mirai botnet that was up to 17.2 million requests per second.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Russian DDoS prevention provider Yandex said it blocked an HTTP pipelining DDoS attack on Sept.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] 2021 that originated from unpatched Mikrotik networking gear.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] In the first half of 2022, the Russian invasion of Ukraine significantly shaped the cyberthreat landscape, with an increase in cyberattacks attributed to both state-sponsored actors and global hacktivist activities.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] The most notable event was a DDoS attack in February, the largest Ukraine has encountered, disrupting government and financial sector services.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] This wave of cyber aggression extended to Western allies like the UK, the US, and Germany.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Particularly, the UK's financial sector saw an increase in DDoS attacks from nation-state actors and hacktivists, aimed at undermining Ukraine's allies.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] In February 2023, Cloudflare faced a 71 million requests per second attack which they claimed was the largest HTTP DDoS attack at the time.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] HTTP DDoS attacks are measured by HTTP requests per second instead of packets per second or bits per second.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] On July 10, 2023, the fanfiction platform Archive of Our Own (AO3) faced DDoS attacks, disrupting services.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Anonymous Sudan, claiming the attack for religious and political reasons, was viewed skeptically by AO3 and experts.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Flashpoint, a threat intelligence vendor, noted the group's past activities but doubted their stated motives.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] AO3, supported by the non-profit Organization for Transformative Works (OTW) and reliant on donations, is unlikely to meet the $30,000 Bitcoin ransom.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] In August 2023, the group of hacktivists NoName057 targeted several Italian financial institutions, through the execution of slow DoS attacks.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] On 14 January 2024, they executed a DDoS attack on Swiss federal websites, prompted by President Zelensky's attendance at the Davos World Economic Forum.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Switzerland's National Cyber Security Centre quickly mitigated the attack, ensuring core federal services remained secure, despite temporary accessibility issues on some websites.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] In October 2023, exploitation of a new vulnerability in the HTTP/2 protocol resulted in the record for largest HTTP DDoS attack being broken twice, once with a 201 million requests per second attack observed by Cloudflare, and again with a 398 million requests per second attack observed by Google.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] In August 2024, Global Secure Layer observed and reported on a record-breaking packet DDoS at 3.15 billion packets per second, which targeted an undisclosed number of unofficial Minecraft game servers.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] In October 2024, the Internet Archive faced two severe DDoS attacks that brought the site completely offline, immediately following a previous attack that leaked records of over 31 million of the site's users.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] The hacktivist group SN_Blackmeta claimed the DDoS attack as retribution for American involvement in the Gaza war, despite the Internet Archive being unaffiliated with the United States government; however, their link with the preceding data leak remains unclear.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Cloudflare claims to have recorded and successfully autonomously blocked a 40-second DDoS attack on 23 September 2025, that reached a peak volume of 22.2 Tbit/s, which would be the largest DDoS attack to date.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Cloudflare has stated that over 404,000 source IPs were used to target one IP address, and that the source IPs were not spoofed.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] According to Cloudflare, this came after several other large-scale DDoS attacks, each consecutively beating the previous record, including a 7.3 Tbit/s attack in May 2025 and an 11.5 Tbit/s attack on 1 September 2025.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Denial-of-service attacks are characterized by an explicit attempt by attackers to prevent legitimate use of a service.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] There are two general forms of DoS attacks: those that crash services and those that flood services.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] The most serious attacks are distributed.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] A distributed denial-of-service (DDoS) attack occurs when multiple systems flood the bandwidth or resources of a targeted system, usually one or more web servers.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] A DDoS attack uses more than one unique IP address or machines, often from thousands of hosts infected with malware.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] A distributed denial of service attack typically involves more than around 3–5 nodes on different networks; fewer nodes may qualify as a DoS attack but is not a DDoS attack.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Most of the time, attackers operate from an endpoint that is not their intended target, for example using another user's machine to attack a server.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] By using another unsuspecting endpoint if it becomes compromised they can then move onto another workstation within the enterprise network.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] However, even faking lots of users and executing a DoS attack, a single attacker with few computers is still very limited in the amount of traffic they can generate.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] If the attacks are from multiple sources, it can be difficult for the host to identify and stop them.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] The scale of DDoS attacks has continued to rise over recent years, by 2016 exceeding a terabit per second.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Some common examples of DDoS attacks are UDP flooding, SYN flooding and DNS amplification.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] A **yo-yo attack** is a specific type of DoS/DDoS aimed at cloud-hosted applications which use autoscaling.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] During the attack, an attacker repeatedly changes between sending a lot of traffic (which causes a scale-up) and stopping the burst (causing a scale-down as a result).
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] An **application layer DDoS attack** (sometimes referred to as **layer 7 DDoS attack**) is a form of DDoS attack where attackers target application-layer processes.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] The attack over-exercises specific functions or features of a website with the intention to disable those functions or features.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] This application-layer attack is different from an entire network attack, and is often used against financial institutions to distract IT and security personnel from security breaches.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] In 2013, application-layer DDoS attacks represented 20% of all DDoS attacks.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] According to research by Akamai Technologies, there have been "51 percent more application layer attacks" from Q4 2013 to Q4 2014 and "16 percent more" from Q3 2014 to Q4 2014.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] In November 2017; Junade Ali, an engineer at Cloudflare noted that whilst network-level attacks continue to be of high capacity, they were occurring less frequently.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Ali further noted that although network-level attacks were becoming less frequent, data from Cloudflare demonstrated that application-layer attacks were still showing no sign of slowing down.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] The simplest DoS attack relies primarily on brute force, flooding the target with an overwhelming flux of packets, oversaturating its connection bandwidth or depleting the target's system resources.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Bandwidth-saturating floods rely on the attacker's ability to generate the overwhelming flux of packets.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] A common way of achieving this today is via distributed denial-of-service, employing a botnet.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] An application layer DDoS attack is done mainly for specific targeted purposes, including disrupting transactions and access to databases.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] It requires fewer resources than network layer attacks but often accompanies them.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] An attack may be disguised to look like legitimate traffic, except it targets specific application packets or functions.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] The attack on the application layer can disrupt services such as the retrieval of information or search functions on a website.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] An **advanced persistent DoS** (APDoS) is associated with an advanced persistent threat and requires specialized DDoS mitigation.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] These attacks can persist for weeks; the longest continuous period noted so far lasted 38 days.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] This attack involved approximately 50+ petabits (50,000+ terabits) of malicious traffic.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Attackers in this scenario may tactically switch between several targets to create a diversion to evade defensive DDoS countermeasures but all the while eventually concentrating the main thrust of the attack onto a single victim.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] In this scenario, attackers with continuous access to several very powerful network resources are capable of sustaining a prolonged campaign generating enormous levels of unamplified DDoS traffic.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Some vendors provide so-called *booter* or *stresser* services, which have simple web-based front ends, and accept payment over the web.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Marketed and promoted as stress-testing tools, they can be used to perform unauthorized denial-of-service attacks, and allow technically unsophisticated attackers access to sophisticated attack tools.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Usually powered by a botnet, the traffic produced by a consumer stresser can range anywhere from 5-50 Gbit/s, which can, in most cases, deny the average home user internet access.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] A Markov-modulated denial-of-service attack occurs when the attacker disrupts control packets using a hidden Markov model.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] A setting in which Markov-model-based attacks are prevalent is online gaming as the disruption of the control packet undermines gameplay and system functionality.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] In cases such as MyDoom and Slowloris, the tools are embedded in malware and launch their attacks without the knowledge of the system owner.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Stacheldraht is a classic example of a DDoS tool.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] It uses a layered structure where the attacker uses a client program to connect to handlers which are compromised systems that issue commands to the zombie agents which in turn facilitate the DDoS attack.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Agents are compromised via the handlers by the attacker using automated routines to exploit vulnerabilities in programs that accept remote connections running on the targeted remote hosts.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Each handler can control up to a thousand agents.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] In other cases a machine may become part of a DDoS attack with the owner's consent, for example, in Operation Payback organized by the group Anonymous.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] The Low Orbit Ion Cannon has typically been used in this way.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Along with High Orbit Ion Cannon a wide variety of DDoS tools are available today, including paid and free versions, with different features available.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] There is an underground market for these in hacker-related forums and IRC channels.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Application-layer attacks employ DoS-causing exploits and can cause server-running software to fill the disk space or consume all available memory or CPU time.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Attacks may use specific packet types or connection requests to saturate finite resources by, for example, occupying the maximum number of open connections or filling the victim's disk space with logs.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] An attacker with shell-level access to a victim's computer may slow it until it is unusable or crash it by using a fork bomb.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Another kind of application-level DoS attack is XDoS (or XML DoS) which can be controlled by modern web application firewalls (WAFs).
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] All attacks belonging to the category of *timeout exploiting*.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Slow DoS attacks implement an application-layer attack.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Examples of threats are Slowloris, establishing pending connections with the victim, or SlowDroid, an attack running on mobile devices.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Another target of DDoS attacks may be to produce added costs for the application operator, when the latter uses resources based on cloud computing.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] In this case, normally application-used resources are tied to a needed quality of service (QoS) level (e.g. responses should be less than 200 ms) and this rule is usually linked to automated software (e.g.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Amazon CloudWatch) to raise more virtual resources from the provider to meet the defined QoS levels for the increased requests.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] The main incentive behind such attacks may be to drive the application owner to raise the elasticity levels to handle the increased application traffic, to cause financial losses, or force them to become less competitive.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] A *banana attack* is another particular type of DoS.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] It involves redirecting outgoing messages from the client back onto the client, preventing outside access, as well as flooding the client with the sent packets.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Pulsing zombies are compromised computers that are directed to launch intermittent and short-lived flooding of victim websites with the intent of merely slowing it rather than crashing it.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] This type of attack, referred to as *degradation-of-service*, can be more difficult to detect and can disrupt and hamper connection to websites for prolonged periods of time, potentially causing more overall disruption than a denial-of-service attack.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Exposure of degradation-of-service attacks is complicated further by the matter of discerning whether the server is really being attacked or is experiencing higher than normal legitimate traffic loads.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] If an attacker mounts an attack from a single host, it would be classified as a DoS attack.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Any attack against availability would be classed as a denial-of-service attack.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] On the other hand, if an attacker uses many systems to simultaneously launch attacks against a remote host, this would be classified as a DDoS attack.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Malware can carry DDoS attack mechanisms; one of the better-known examples of this was MyDoom.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Its DoS mechanism was triggered on a specific date and time.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] This type of DDoS involved hardcoding the target IP address before releasing the malware and no further interaction was necessary to launch the attack.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] A system may also be compromised with a trojan containing a zombie agent.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Attackers can also break into systems using automated tools that exploit flaws in programs that listen for connections from remote hosts.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] This scenario primarily concerns systems acting as servers on the web.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] It uses a layered structure where the attacker uses a client program to connect to handlers, which are compromised systems that issue commands to the zombie agents, which in turn facilitate the DDoS attack.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Agents are compromised via the handlers by the attacker.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] In some cases a machine may become part of a DDoS attack with the owner's consent, for example, in Operation Payback, organized by the group Anonymous.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] These attacks can use different types of internet packets such as TCP, UDP, ICMP, etc.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] These collections of compromised systems are known as botnets.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] DDoS tools like Stacheldraht still use classic DoS attack methods centered on IP spoofing and amplification like smurf attacks and fraggle attacks (types of bandwidth consumption attacks).
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] SYN floods (a resource starvation attack) may also be used.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Newer tools can use DNS servers for DoS purposes.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Unlike MyDoom's DDoS mechanism, botnets can be turned against any IP address.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Script kiddies use them to deny the availability of well known websites to legitimate users.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] More sophisticated attackers use DDoS tools for the purposes of extortion – including against their business rivals.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] It has been reported that there are new attacks from internet of things (IoT) devices that have been involved in denial of service attacks.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] One such attack peaked at around 20,000 requests per second; it came from around 900 CCTV cameras.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] UK's GCHQ has tools built for DDoS, named PREDATORS FACE and ROLLING THUNDER.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Simple attacks such as SYN floods may appear with a wide range of source IP addresses, giving the appearance of a distributed DoS.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] These flood attacks do not require completion of the TCP three-way handshake and attempt to exhaust the destination SYN queue or the server bandwidth.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Because the source IP addresses can be trivially spoofed, an attack could come from a limited set of sources, or may even originate from a single host.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Stack enhancements such as SYN cookies may be effective mitigation against SYN queue flooding but do not address bandwidth exhaustion.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] In 2022, TCP attacks were the leading method in DDoS incidents, accounting for 63% of all DDoS activity.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] This includes tactics like TCP SYN, TCP ACK, and TCP floods.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] With TCP being the most widespread networking protocol, its attacks are expected to remain prevalent in the DDoS threat scene.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] In 2015, DDoS botnets such as DD4BC grew in prominence, taking aim at financial institutions.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Cyber-extortionists typically begin with a low-level attack and a warning that a larger attack will be carried out if a ransom is not paid in bitcoin.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Security experts recommend targeted websites to not pay the ransom.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] The attackers tend to get into an extended extortion scheme once they recognize that the target is ready to pay.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] First discovered in 2009, the HTTP slow POST attack sends a complete, legitimate HTTP POST header, which includes a *Content-Length* field to specify the size of the message body to follow.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] However, the attacker then proceeds to send the actual message body at an extremely slow rate (e.g.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Due to the entire message being correct and complete, the target server will attempt to obey the *Content-Length* field in the header and wait for the entire body of the message to be transmitted, which can take a very long time.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] The attacker establishes hundreds or even thousands of such connections until all resources for incoming connections on the victim server are exhausted, making any further connections impossible until all data has been sent.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] It is notable that unlike many other DoS or DDoS attacks, which try to subdue the server by overloading its network or CPU, an HTTP slow POST attack targets the *logical* resources of the victim, which means the victim would still have enough network bandwidth and processing power to operate.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Combined with the fact that the Apache HTTP Server will, by default, accept requests up to 2GB in size, this attack can be particularly powerful.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] HTTP slow POST attacks are difficult to differentiate from legitimate connections and are therefore able to bypass some protection systems.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] OWASP, an open source web application security project, released a tool to test the security of servers against this type of attack.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] A Challenge Collapsar (CC) attack is an attack where standard HTTP requests are sent to a targeted web server frequently.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] The Uniform Resource Identifiers (URIs) in the requests require complicated time-consuming algorithms or database operations which may exhaust the resources of the targeted web server.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] In 2004, a Chinese hacker nicknamed KiKi invented a hacking tool to send these kinds of requests to attack a NSFOCUS firewall named Collapsar, and thus the hacking tool was known as Challenge Collapsar, or *CC* for short.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Consequently, this type of attack got the name *CC attack*.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] A smurf attack relies on misconfigured network devices that allow packets to be sent to all computer hosts on a particular network via the broadcast address of the network, rather than a specific machine.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] The attacker will send large numbers of IP packets with the source address faked to appear to be the address of the victim.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Most devices on a network will, by default, respond to this by sending a reply to the source IP address.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] If the number of machines on the network that receive and respond to these packets is very large, the victim's computer will be flooded with traffic.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] This overloads the victim's computer and can even make it unusable during such an attack.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Ping flood is based on sending the victim an overwhelming number of ping packets, usually using the *ping* command from Unix-like hosts.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] It is very simple to launch, the primary requirement being access to greater bandwidth than the victim.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Ping of death is based on sending the victim a malformed ping packet, which will lead to a system crash on a vulnerable system.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] The BlackNurse attack is an example of an attack taking advantage of the required Destination Port Unreachable ICMP packets.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] A specific example of a nuke attack that gained some prominence is the WinNuke, which exploited the vulnerability in the NetBIOS handler in Windows 95.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] A string of out-of-band data was sent to TCP port 139 of the victim's machine, causing it to lock up and display a Blue Screen of Death.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Attackers have found a way to exploit a number of bugs in peer-to-peer servers to initiate DDoS attacks.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] The most aggressive of these peer-to-peer-DDoS attacks exploits the DC++ file sharing network.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] With peer-to-peer attacks there is no botnet and the attacker does not have to communicate with the clients it subverts.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Instead, the attacker acts as a *puppet master*, instructing clients of large peer-to-peer file sharing hubs to disconnect from their peer-to-peer network and to connect to the victim's website instead.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Permanent denial-of-service (PDoS), also known loosely as phlashing, is an attack that damages a system so badly that it requires replacement or reinstallation of hardware.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Unlike the distributed denial-of-service attack, a PDoS attack exploits security flaws which allow remote administration on the management interfaces of the victim's hardware, such as routers, printers, or other networking hardware.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] The PDoS is a pure hardware-targeted attack that can be much faster and requires fewer resources than using a botnet in a DDoS attack.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Because of these features, and the potential and high probability of security exploits on network-enabled embedded devices, this technique has come to the attention of numerous hacking communities.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] BrickerBot, a piece of malware that targeted IoT devices, used PDoS attacks to disable its targets.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] PhlashDance is a tool created by Rich Smith (an employee of Hewlett-Packard's Systems Security Lab) used to detect and demonstrate PDoS vulnerabilities at the 2008 EUSecWest Applied Security Conference in London, UK.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] A distributed denial-of-service attack may involve sending forged requests of some type to a very large number of computers that will reply to the requests.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Using Internet Protocol address spoofing, the source address is set to that of the targeted victim, which means all the replies will go to (and flood) the target.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] This reflected attack form is sometimes called a distributed reflective denial-of-service (DRDoS) attack.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] ICMP echo request attacks (Smurf attacks) can be considered one form of reflected attack, as the flooding hosts send Echo Requests to the broadcast addresses of mis-configured networks, thereby enticing hosts to send Echo Reply packets to the victim.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Some early DDoS programs implemented a distributed form of this attack.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Amplification attacks are used to magnify the bandwidth that is sent to a victim.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Many services can be exploited to act as reflectors, some harder to block than others.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] DNS amplification attacks involves an attacker sending a DNS name lookup request to one or more public DNS servers, spoofing the source IP address of the targeted victim.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] The attacker tries to request as much information as possible, thus amplifying the DNS response that is sent to the targeted victim.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Since the size of the request is significantly smaller than the response, the attacker is easily able to increase the amount of traffic directed at the target.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP) and Network Time Protocol (NTP) can also be exploited as reflectors in an amplification attack.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] An example of an amplified DDoS attack through the NTP is through a command called monlist, which sends the details of the last 600 hosts that have requested the time from the NTP server back to the requester.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] A small request to this time server can be sent using a spoofed source IP address of some victim, which results in a response 556.9 times the size of the request being sent to the victim.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] This becomes amplified when using botnets that all send requests with the same spoofed IP source, which will result in a massive amount of data being sent back to the victim.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] It is very difficult to defend against these types of attacks because the response data is coming from legitimate servers.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] These attack requests are also sent through UDP, which does not require a connection to the server.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] This means that the source IP is not verified when a request is received by the server.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] To bring awareness of these vulnerabilities, campaigns have been started that are dedicated to finding amplification vectors which have led to people fixing their resolvers or having the resolvers shut down completely.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] The Mirai botnet works by using a computer worm to infect hundreds of thousands of IoT devices across the internet.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] The worm propagates through networks and systems taking control of poorly protected IoT devices such as thermostats, Wi-Fi-enabled clocks, and washing machines.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] The owner or user will usually have no immediate indication of when the device becomes infected.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] The IoT device itself is not the direct target of the attack; it is used as part of a larger attack.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Once the hacker has enslaved the desired number of devices, they instruct the devices to try to contact an ISP.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] In October 2016, a Mirai botnet attacked Dyn which is the ISP for sites such as Twitter, Netflix, etc.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] As soon as this occurred, these websites were all unreachable for several hours.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] RUDY attack targets web applications by starvation of available sessions on the web server.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Much like Slowloris, RUDY keeps sessions at a halt using never-ending POST transmissions and sending an arbitrarily large content-length header value.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Manipulating maximum segment size and selective acknowledgement (SACK) may be used by a remote peer to cause a denial of service by an integer overflow in the Linux kernel, potentially causing a kernel panic.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] The shrew attack is a denial-of-service attack on the Transmission Control Protocol where the attacker employs man-in-the-middle techniques.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] It exploits a weakness in TCP's re-transmission timeout mechanism, using short synchronized bursts of traffic to disrupt TCP connections on the same link.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] A slow read attack sends legitimate application layer requests, but reads responses very slowly, keeping connections open longer hoping to exhaust the server's connection pool.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] The slow read is achieved by advertising a very small number for the TCP Receive Window size, and at the same time emptying clients' TCP receive buffer slowly, which causes a very low data flow rate.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] A sophisticated low-bandwidth DDoS attack is a form of DoS that uses less traffic and increases its effectiveness by aiming at a weak point in the victim's system design, i.e., the attacker sends traffic consisting of complicated requests to the system.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Essentially, a sophisticated DDoS attack is lower in cost due to its use of less traffic, is smaller in size making it more difficult to identify, and it can hurt systems which are protected by flow control mechanisms.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] A SYN flood occurs when a host sends a flood of TCP/SYN packets, often with a forged sender address.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Each of these packets is handled like a connection request, causing the server to spawn a half-open connection, send back a TCP/SYN-ACK packet, and wait for a packet in response from the sender address.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] However, because the sender's address is forged, the response never comes.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] These half-open connections exhaust the available connections the server can make, keeping it from responding to legitimate requests until after the attack ends.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] A **teardrop attack** involves sending mangled IP fragments with overlapping, oversized payloads to the target machine.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] This can crash various operating systems because of a bug in their TCP/IP fragmentation re-assembly code.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Windows 3.1x, Windows 95 and Windows NT operating systems, as well as versions of Linux before versions 2.0.32 and 2.1.63 are vulnerable to this attack.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] One of the fields in an IP header is the *fragment offset* field, indicating the starting position, or offset, of the data contained in a fragmented packet relative to the data in the original packet.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] If the sum of the offset and size of one fragmented packet differs from that of the next fragmented packet, the packets overlap.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] When this happens, a server vulnerable to teardrop attacks is unable to reassemble the packets resulting in a denial-of-service condition.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Voice over IP has made abusive origination of large numbers of telephone voice calls inexpensive and easily automated while permitting call origins to be misrepresented through caller ID spoofing.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] TDoS can exist even without Internet telephony.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] In the 2002 New Hampshire Senate election phone jamming scandal, telemarketers were used to flood political opponents with spurious calls to jam phone banks on election day.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Widespread publication of a number can also flood it with enough calls to render it unusable, as happened by accident in 1981 with multiple +1-area code-867-5309 subscribers inundated by hundreds of calls daily in response to the song "867-5309/Jenny".
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] TDoS differs from other telephone harassment (such as prank calls and obscene phone calls) by the number of calls originated.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] By occupying lines continuously with repeated automated calls, the victim is prevented from making or receiving both routine and emergency telephone calls.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Related exploits include SMS flooding attacks and black fax or continuous fax transmission by using a loop of paper at the sender.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] It takes more router resources to drop a packet with a TTL value of 1 or less than it does to forward a packet with a higher TTL value.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] When a packet is dropped due to TTL expiry, the router CPU must generate and send an ICMP time exceeded response.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Generating many of these responses can overload the router's CPU.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] A UPnP attack uses an existing vulnerability in Universal Plug and Play (UPnP) protocol to get past network security and flood a target's network and servers.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] The attack is based on a DNS amplification technique, but the attack mechanism is a UPnP router that forwards requests from one outer source to another.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] The UPnP router returns the data on an unexpected UDP port from a bogus IP address, making it harder to take simple action to shut down the traffic flood.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] According to the Imperva researchers, the most effective way to stop this attack is for companies to lock down UPnP routers.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] In 2014, it was discovered that Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP) was being used in DDoS attacks known as an SSDP reflection attac*k* *with amplification*.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Many devices, including some residential routers, have a vulnerability in the UPnP software that allows an attacker to get replies from UDP port 1900 to a destination address of their choice.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] With a botnet of thousands of devices, the attackers can generate sufficient packet rates and occupy bandwidth to saturate links, causing the denial of service.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Because of this weakness, the network company Cloudflare has described SSDP as the "Stupidly Simple DDoS Protocol".
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Defensive responses to denial-of-service attacks typically involve the use of a combination of attack detection, traffic classification and response tools, aiming to block traffic the tools identify as illegitimate and allow traffic that they identify as legitimate.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] A list of response tools include the following.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] All traffic destined to the victim is diverted to pass through a *cleaning center* or a *scrubbing center* via various methods such as: changing the victim IP address in the DNS system, tunneling methods (GRE/VRF, MPLS, SDN), proxies, digital cross connects, or even direct circuits.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] The cleaning center separates *bad* traffic (DDoS and also other common internet attacks) and only passes good legitimate traffic to the victim server.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] The victim needs central connectivity to the Internet to use this kind of service unless they happen to be located within the same facility as the cleaning center.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] DDoS attacks can overwhelm any type of hardware firewall, and passing malicious traffic through large and mature networks becomes more and more effective and economically sustainable against DDoS.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Application front-end hardware is intelligent hardware placed on the network before traffic reaches the servers.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] It can be used on networks in conjunction with routers and switches and as part of bandwidth management.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Application front-end hardware analyzes data packets as they enter the network, and identifies and drops dangerous or suspicious flows.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Approaches to detection of DDoS attacks against cloud-based applications may be based on an application layer analysis, indicating whether incoming bulk traffic is legitimate.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] These approaches mainly rely on an identified path of value inside the application and monitor the progress of requests on this path, through markers called *key completion indicators*.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] In essence, these techniques are statistical methods of assessing the behavior of incoming requests to detect if something unusual or abnormal is going on.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] An analogy is to a brick-and-mortar department store where customers spend, on average, a known percentage of their time on different activities such as picking up items and examining them, putting them back, filling a basket, waiting to pay, paying, and leaving.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] If a mob of customers arrived in the store and spent all their time picking up items and putting them back, but never made any purchases, this could be flagged as unusual behavior.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] With blackhole routing, all the traffic to the attacked DNS or IP address is sent to a *black hole* (null interface or a non-existent server).
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] To be more efficient and avoid affecting network connectivity, it can be managed by the ISP.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] A DNS sinkhole routes traffic to a valid IP address which analyzes traffic and rejects bad packets.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Sinkholing may not be efficient for severe attacks.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Intrusion prevention systems (IPS) are effective if the attacks have signatures associated with them.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] However, the trend among attacks is to have legitimate content but bad intent.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Intrusion-prevention systems that work on content recognition cannot block behavior-based DoS attacks.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] An ASIC based IPS may detect and block denial-of-service attacks because they have the processing power and the granularity to analyze the attacks and act like a circuit breaker in an automated way.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] More focused on the problem than IPS, a DoS defense system (DDS) can block connection-based DoS attacks and those with legitimate content but bad intent.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] A DDS can also address both protocol attacks (such as teardrop and ping of death) and rate-based attacks (such as ICMP floods and SYN floods).
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] DDS has a purpose-built system that can easily identify and obstruct denial of service attacks at a greater speed than a software-based system.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] In the case of a simple attack, a firewall can be adjusted to deny all incoming traffic from the attackers, based on protocols, ports, or the originating IP addresses.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] More complex attacks will however be hard to block with simple rules: for example, if there is an ongoing attack on port 80 (web service), it is not possible to drop all incoming traffic on this port because doing so will prevent the server from receiving and serving legitimate traffic.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Additionally, firewalls may be too deep in the network hierarchy, with routers being adversely affected before the traffic gets to the firewall.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Also, many security tools still do not support IPv6 or may not be configured properly, so the firewalls may be bypassed during the attacks.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Similar to switches, routers have some rate-limiting and ACL capabilities.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Most routers can be easily overwhelmed under a DoS attack.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Nokia SR-OS using FP4 or FP5 processors offers DDoS protection.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Nokia SR-OS also uses big data analytics-based Nokia Deepfield Defender for DDoS protection.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Cisco IOS has optional features that can reduce the impact of flooding.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Most switches have some rate-limiting and ACL capability.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Some switches provide automatic or system-wide rate limiting, traffic shaping, delayed binding (TCP splicing), deep packet inspection and bogon filtering (bogus IP filtering) to detect and remediate DoS attacks through automatic rate filtering and WAN Link failover and balancing.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] These schemes will work as long as the DoS attacks can be prevented by using them.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] For example, SYN flood can be prevented using delayed binding or TCP splicing.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Similarly, content-based DoS may be prevented using deep packet inspection.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Attacks using Martian packets can be prevented using bogon filtering.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Automatic rate filtering can work as long as set rate thresholds have been set correctly.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] WAN-link failover will work as long as both links have a DoS prevention mechanism.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Threats may be associated with specific TCP or UDP port numbers.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Blocking these ports at the firewall can mitigate an attack.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] For example, in an SSDP reflection attack, the key mitigation is to block incoming UDP traffic on port 1900.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Blocking specific Time to live (TTL) values based on the network path length can be a viable option for blocking spoofed attacks.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] An unintentional denial-of-service can occur when a system ends up denied, not due to a deliberate attack by a single individual or group of individuals, but simply due to a sudden enormous spike in popularity.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] This can happen when an extremely popular website posts a prominent link to a second, less well-prepared site, for example, as part of a news story.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] The result is that a significant proportion of the primary site's regular users – potentially hundreds of thousands of people – click that link in the space of a few hours, having the same effect on the target website as a DDoS attack.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] A VIPDoS is the same, but specifically when the link was posted by a celebrity.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] When Michael Jackson died in 2009, websites such as Google and Twitter slowed down or even crashed.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Many sites' servers thought the requests were from a virus or spyware trying to cause a denial-of-service attack, warning users that their queries looked like "automated requests from a computer virus or spyware application".
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] News sites and link sites – sites whose primary function is to provide links to interesting content elsewhere on the Internet – are most likely to cause this phenomenon.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] The canonical example is the Slashdot effect when receiving traffic from Slashdot.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] It is also known as "the Reddit hug of death" and "the Digg effect".
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Similar unintentional denial-of-service can also occur via other media, e.g. when a URL is mentioned on television.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] In March 2014, after Malaysia Airlines Flight 370 went missing, DigitalGlobe launched a crowdsourcing service on which users could help search for the missing jet in satellite images.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] The response overwhelmed the company's servers.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] An unintentional denial-of-service may also result from a prescheduled event created by the website itself, as was the case of the Census in Australia in 2016.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Legal action has been taken in at least one such case.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] In 2006, Universal Tube & Rollform Equipment Corporation sued YouTube: massive numbers of would-be YouTube.com users accidentally typed the tube company's URL, utube.com.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] As a result, the tube company ended up having to spend large amounts of money on upgrading its bandwidth.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Routers have also been known to create unintentional DoS attacks, as both D-Link and Netgear routers have overloaded NTP servers by flooding them without respecting the restrictions of client types or geographical limitations.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] In computer network security, backscatter is a side-effect of a spoofed denial-of-service attack.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] In this kind of attack, the attacker spoofs the source address in IP packets sent to the victim.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] In general, the victim machine cannot distinguish between the spoofed packets and legitimate packets, so the victim responds to the spoofed packets as it normally would.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] These response packets are known as backscatter.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] If the attacker is spoofing source addresses randomly, the backscatter response packets from the victim will be sent back to random destinations.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] This effect can be used by network telescopes as indirect evidence of such attacks.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] The term *backscatter analysis* refers to observing backscatter packets arriving at a statistically significant portion of the IP address space to determine the characteristics of DoS attacks and victims.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Many jurisdictions have laws under which denial-of-service attacks are illegal.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] UNCTAD highlights that 156 countries, or 80% globally, have enacted cybercrime laws to combat its widespread impact.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Adoption rates vary by region, with Europe at a 91% rate, and Africa at 72%.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] In the US, denial-of-service attacks may be considered a federal crime under the Computer Fraud and Abuse Act with penalties that include years of imprisonment.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] The Computer Crime and Intellectual Property Section of the US Department of Justice handles cases of DoS and DDoS.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] In one example, in July 2019, Austin Thompson, aka DerpTrolling, was sentenced to 27 months in prison and $95,000 in restitution by a federal court for conducting multiple DDoS attacks on major video gaming companies, disrupting their systems for hours to days.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] In European countries, committing criminal denial-of-service attacks may, as a minimum, lead to arrest.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] The United Kingdom is unusual in that it specifically outlawed denial-of-service attacks and set a maximum penalty of 10 years in prison with the Police and Justice Act 2006, which amended Section 3 of the Computer Misuse Act 1990.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] In January 2019, Europol announced that "actions are currently underway worldwide to track down the users" of Webstresser.org, a former DDoS marketplace that was shut down in April 2018 as part of Operation PowerOFF.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] Europol said UK police were conducting a number of "live operations" targeting over 250 users of Webstresser and other DDoS services.
[src:bot-management/denial-of-service-attack] On January 7, 2013, Anonymous posted a petition on the whitehouse.gov site asking that DDoS be recognized as a legal form of protest similar to the Occupy movement, the claim being that the similarity in the purpose of both is same.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] An **Internet bot** (also called a **web robot** or **robot**), or simply **bot**, is a software application that runs automated tasks (scripts) on the Internet, usually with the intent to imitate human activity, such as messaging, on a large scale.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] An Internet bot plays the client role in a client–server model whereas the server role is usually played by web servers.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] Internet bots are able to perform simple and repetitive tasks much faster than a person could ever do.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] The most extensive use of bots is for web crawling, in which an automated script fetches, analyzes and files information from web servers.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] More than half of all web traffic is generated by bots.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] Efforts by web servers to restrict bots vary.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] Some servers have a `robots.txt` file that contains the rules requesting how bots should behave on the website.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] Any bot that does not follow the rules could, in theory, be denied access to the affected website, while in practice, a website owner cannot force a bot to follow the rules or ensure that a bot's creator or implementer reads or acknowledges the robots.txt file.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] Some bots are "good", e.g. search engine spiders, while other "bad" bots are used to launch malicious attacks on websites or applications, such as political campaigns.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] Some bots communicate with users of Internet-based services via instant messaging (IM), Internet Relay Chat (IRC), or other web interfaces such as Facebook bots and Twitter bots.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] These chatbots may allow people to ask questions in plain English and then formulate a response.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] Such bots can often handle reporting weather, postal code information, sports scores, currency or other unit conversions, etc.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] Others are used for entertainment, such as SmarterChild on AOL Instant Messenger and MSN Messenger.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] Additional roles of an IRC bot may be to listen on a conversation channel, and to comment on certain phrases uttered by the participants (based on pattern matching).
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] This is sometimes used as a help service for new users or to censor profanity.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] Social bots are sets of algorithms that take on the duties of repetitive sets of instructions in order to establish a service or connection among social networking users.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] Among the various designs of networking bots, the most common are chat bots, algorithms designed to converse with a human user, and social bots, algorithms designed to mimic human behaviors to converse with patterns similar to those of a human user.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] The history of social botting can be traced back to Alan Turing in the 1950s and his vision of designing sets of instructional code approved by the Turing test.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] In the 1960s Joseph Weizenbaum created ELIZA, a natural language processing computer program considered an early indicator of artificial intelligence algorithms.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] ELIZA inspired computer programmers to design task-oriented programs that can match behavior patterns to their sets of instructions.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] As a result, natural language processing has become an influencing factor in the development of artificial intelligence and social bots.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] And as information and thought see a progressive mass spreading on social media websites, innovative technological advancements are made following the same pattern.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] Reports of political interferences in recent elections, including the 2016 US and 2017 UK general elections, have set the notion of bots being more prevalent because of the ethics that is challenged between the bot's design and the bot's designer.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] In the case of Twitter, most of these bots are programmed with search filter capabilities that target keywords and phrases favoring political agendas and then retweet them.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] While the attention of bots is programmed to spread unverified information throughout the social media platforms, it is a challenge that programmers face in the wake of a hostile political climate.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] There has been a great deal of controversy about the use of bots in an automated trading function.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] Auction website eBay took legal action in an attempt to suppress a third-party company from using bots to look for bargains on its site; this approach backfired on eBay and attracted the attention of further bots.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] The United Kingdom-based bet exchange, Betfair, saw such a large amount of traffic coming from bots that it launched a WebService API aimed at bot programmers, through which it can actively manage bot interactions.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] Bot farms are known to be used in online app stores, like the Apple App Store and Google Play, to manipulate positions or increase positive ratings/reviews.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] A rapidly growing form of internet bot is the chatbot.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] From 2016, when Facebook Messenger allowed developers to place chatbots on their platform, there has been an exponential growth of their use on that app alone.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] 30,000 bots were created for Messenger in the first six months, rising to 100,000 by September 2017.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] Avi Ben Ezra, CTO of SnatchBot, told Forbes that evidence from the use of their chatbot building platform pointed to a near future saving of millions of hours of human labor as 'live chat' on websites was replaced with bots.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] Companies use internet bots to increase online engagement and streamline communication.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] Companies often use bots to cut down on cost; instead of employing people to communicate with consumers, companies have developed new ways to be efficient.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] These chatbots are used to answer customers' questions; for example, Domino's developed a chatbot that can take orders via Facebook Messenger.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] Chatbots allow companies to allocate their employees' time to other tasks.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] One example of the malicious use of bots is the coordination and operation of an automated attack on networked computers, such as a denial-of-service attack by a botnet.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] Internet bots or web bots can also be used to commit click fraud and more recently have appeared around MMORPG games as computer game bots.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] Another category is represented by spambots, internet bots that attempt to spam large amounts of content on the Internet, usually adding advertising links.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] More than 94.2% of websites have experienced a bot attack.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] Registration bots that sign up a specific email address to numerous services in order to have the confirmation messages flood the email inbox and distract from important messages indicating a security breach.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] Bots that buy up high-demand seats for concerts, operated by ticket brokers who resell the tickets.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] These bots run through the purchase process of entertainment event-ticketing sites and obtain as many seats as they can.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] Bots that are used in massively multiplayer online role-playing games to farm for resources that would otherwise take significant time or effort to obtain, which can be a concern for online in-game economies.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] Bots that increase traffic counts on analytics reporting to extract money from advertisers.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] A study by Comscore found that over half of ads shown across thousands of campaigns between May 2012 and February 2013 were not served to human users.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] Bots used on internet forums to automatically post inflammatory or nonsensical posts to disrupt the forum and anger users.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] in 2012, journalist Percy von Lipinski reported that he discovered millions of bots or botted or pinged views at CNN iReport.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] CNN iReport quietly removed millions of views from the account of iReporter Chris Morrow.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] It is not known if the ad revenue received by CNN from the fake views was ever returned to the advertisers.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] The most widely used anti-bot technique is CAPTCHA.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] Examples of providers include Recaptcha, Minteye, Solve Media and NuCaptcha.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] However, CAPTCHAs are not foolproof in preventing bots, as they can often be circumvented by computer character recognition, security holes, and outsourcing CAPTCHA solving to cheap laborers.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] In the case of academic surveys, protection against auto test-taking bots is essential for maintaining accuracy and consistency in the results of the survey.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] Without proper precautions against these bots, the results of a survey can become skewed or inaccurate.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] Researchers indicate that the best way to keep bots out of surveys is to not allow them to enter to begin with.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] The survey should have participants from a reliable source, such as an existing department or group at work.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] This way, malicious bots don't have the opportunity to infiltrate the study.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] Another form of protection against bots is a CAPTCHA test as mentioned in a previous section, which stands for "Completely Automated Public Turing Test".
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] This test is often used to quickly distinguish a real user from a bot by posing a challenge that a human could easily do but a bot would not.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] This could be something like recognizing distorted letters or numbers, or picking out specific parts of an image, such as traffic lights on a busy street.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] CAPTCHAs are a great form of protection due to their ability to be completed quickly, with low effort and easy implementation.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] There are also dedicated companies that specialize in protection against bots, including ones like DataDome, Akamai and Imperva.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] These companies offer defense systems to their clients to protect them against DDoS attacks, infrastructure attacks, and overall cybersecurity.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] While the pricing rates of these companies can often be expensive, the services offered can be crucial both for large corporations and small businesses.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] There are two main concerns with bots: clarity and face-to-face support.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] The cultural background of human beings affects the way they communicate with social bots.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] Others recognize that online bots can "masquerade" as humans online and have become highly aware of their presence.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] Due to this, some users are becoming unsure when interacting with a social bot.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] Many people believe that bots are vastly less intelligent than humans, so they are not worthy of our respect.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] Min-Sun Kim proposed five concerns or issues that may arise when communicating with a social robot, and they are avoiding the damage of people's feelings, minimizing impositions, disapproval from others, clarity issues, and how effective their messages may come across.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] People who oppose social robots argue that they also take away from the genuine creations of human relationships.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] Opposition to social bots also notes that the use of social bots adds a new, unnecessary layer to privacy protection.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] Many users call for stricter legislation in relation to social bots to ensure private information remains preserved.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] The discussion of what to do with social bots and how far they should go remains ongoing.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] In recent years, political discussion platforms and politics on social media have become highly unstable and volatile.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] With the introduction of social bots on the political discussion scene, many users worry about their effect on the discussion and election outcomes.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] The biggest offender on the social media side is X (previously Twitter), where heated political discussions are raised both by bots and real users.
[src:bot-management/internet-bot] The result is a misuse of political discussion on these platforms and a general mistrust among users of what they see.
[src:bot-management/rate-limiting] In computer networks, **rate limiting** is used to control the rate of requests sent or received by a network interface controller.
[src:bot-management/rate-limiting] It can be used to prevent DoS attacks and limit web scraping.
[src:bot-management/rate-limiting] Research indicates flooding rates for one zombie machine are in excess of 20 HTTP GET requests per second, legitimate rates much less.
[src:bot-management/rate-limiting] Rate limiting should be used along with throttling pattern to minimize the number of throttling errors.
[src:bot-management/rate-limiting] Hardware appliances can limit the rate of requests on layer 4 or 5 of the OSI model.
[src:bot-management/rate-limiting] Rate limiting can be induced by the network protocol stack of the sender due to a received ECN-marked packet and also by the network scheduler of any router along the way.
[src:bot-management/rate-limiting] While a hardware appliance can limit the rate for a given range of IP-addresses on layer 4, it risks blocking a network with many users which are masked by NAT with a single IP address of an ISP.
[src:bot-management/rate-limiting] Deep packet inspection can be used to filter on the session layer but will effectively disarm encryption protocols like TLS and SSL between the appliance and the protocol server (i.e. web server).
[src:bot-management/rate-limiting] Protocol servers using a request / response model, such as FTP servers or typically Web servers may use a central in-memory key-value database, like Redis or Aerospike, for session management.
[src:bot-management/rate-limiting] A rate limiting algorithm is used to check if the user session (or IP address) has to be limited based on the information in the session cache.
[src:bot-management/rate-limiting] In case a client made too many requests within a given time frame, HTTP servers can respond with status code 429: Too Many Requests.
[src:bot-management/rate-limiting] However, in some cases (i.e. web servers) the session management and rate limiting algorithm should be built into the application (used for dynamic content) running on the web server, rather than the web server itself.
[src:bot-management/rate-limiting] When a protocol server or a network device notice that the configured request limit is reached, then it will offload new requests and not respond to them.
[src:bot-management/rate-limiting] Sometimes they may be added to a queue to be processed once the input rate reaches an acceptable level, but at peak times the request rate can even exceed the capacities of such queues and requests have to be thrown away.
[src:bot-management/rate-limiting] Data centers widely use rate limiting to control the share of resources given to different tenants and applications according to their service level agreement.
[src:bot-management/rate-limiting] A variety of rate limiting techniques are applied in data centers using software and hardware.
[src:bot-management/rate-limiting] Virtualized data centers may also apply rate limiting at the hypervisor layer.
[src:bot-management/rate-limiting] Two important performance metrics of rate limiters in data centers are resource footprint (memory and CPU usage) which determines scalability, and precision.
[src:bot-management/rate-limiting] There usually exists a trade-off, that is, higher precision can be achieved by dedicating more resources to the rate limiters.
[src:bot-management/rate-limiting] A considerable body of research with focus on improving performance of rate limiting in data centers.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] Scraping a web page involves fetching it and then extracting data from it.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] Fetching is the downloading of a page (which a browser does when a user views a page).
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] Therefore, web crawling is a main component of web scraping, to fetch pages for later processing.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] Having fetched, extraction can take place.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] The content of a page may be parsed, searched and reformatted, and its data copied into a spreadsheet or loaded into a database.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] Web scrapers typically take something out of a page, to make use of it for another purpose somewhere else.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] An example would be finding and copying names and telephone numbers, companies and their URLs, or e-mail addresses to a list (contact scraping).
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] Another example is collecting competitors product prices for marketing purposes, which can involve gathering large-scale pricing datasets from e-commerce websites and analysing them using data science techniques such as trend analysis, predictive modelling, and competitive benchmarking.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] Web pages are built using text-based markup languages (HTML and XHTML), and frequently contain a wealth of data in text form.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] However, most web pages are designed for human end-users and not for ease of automated use.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] As a result, specialized tools and software have been developed to facilitate the scraping of web pages.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] Web scraping applications include market research, price comparison, content monitoring and artificial intelligence.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] Businesses rely on web scraping services to efficiently gather and utilize this data.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] Newer forms of web scraping involve monitoring data feeds from web servers.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] For example, JSON is commonly used as a transport mechanism between the client and the web server.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] There are methods that some websites use to prevent web scraping, such as detecting and disallowing bots from crawling (viewing) their pages.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] In response, web scraping systems use techniques involving DOM parsing, computer vision and natural language processing to simulate human-like browsing to enable gathering web page content for offline parsing.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] After the birth of the World Wide Web in 1989, the first web robot, World Wide Web Wanderer, was created in June 1993, which was intended only to measure the size of the web.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] In December 1993, the first crawler-based web search engine, JumpStation, was launched.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] As there were fewer websites available on the web, search engines at that time used to rely on human administrators to collect and format links.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] In comparison, Jump Station was the first WWW search engine to rely on a web robot.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] In 2000, the first Web API and API crawler were created.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] In 2000, Salesforce and eBay launched their own API, with which programmers could access and download some of the data available to the public.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] Since then, many websites offer web APIs for people to access their public database.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] Data extraction techniques range from manual collection to sophisticated automated systems.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] Advanced methods analyze the underlying structure of web pages to transform unstructured content into a machine-readable format.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] These techniques utilize text processing or artificial intelligence, aligning with the technical goals of the Semantic Web.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] The simplest form of web scraping is manual copying and pasting of data from a web page into a text file or spreadsheet.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] This approach requires no technical tools and can be used when automated scraping is blocked by website restrictions or when human judgment is necessary to interpret complex content.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] However, manual scraping is highly inefficient for large datasets, as it is time-consuming, prone to human error, and mentally exhausting.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] For this reason, it is generally considered impractical compared to automated methods, except in cases where automation is not feasible.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] A simple approach to extract information from web pages is to use the UNIX grep command or regular expression-matching facilities of programming languages (for instance Perl or Python), in order to find text matching a specified pattern.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] Static and dynamic web pages can be retrieved by posting HTTP requests to the remote web server using socket programming.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] Many websites have large collections of pages generated dynamically from an underlying structured source, like a database.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] Data of the same category are typically encoded into similar pages by a common script or template.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] In data mining, a program that detects such templates in a particular information source, extracts its content, and translates it into a relational form, is called a wrapper.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] Wrapper generation algorithms assume that input pages of a wrapper induction system conform to a common template and that they can be easily identified in terms of a URL common scheme.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] Moreover, some semi-structured data query languages, such as XQuery and the HTQL, can be used to parse HTML pages and to retrieve and transform page content.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] By using a program such as Selenium or Playwright, developers can control a web browser such as Chrome or Firefox to load, navigate, and retrieve data from websites.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] This method can be especially useful for scraping data from dynamic sites since a web browser will fully load each page.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] Once an entire page is loaded, developers can access and parse the DOM using an expression language such as XPath.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] There are several companies that have developed vertical specific harvesting platforms.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] These platforms create and monitor a multitude of "bots" for specific verticals with no "man in the loop" (no direct human involvement), and no work related to a specific target site.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] The preparation involves establishing the knowledge base for the entire vertical and then the platform creates the bots automatically.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] The platform's robustness is measured by the quality of the information it retrieves (usually number of fields) and its scalability (how quick it can scale up to hundreds or thousands of sites).
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] This scalability is mostly used to target the Long Tail of sites that common aggregators find complicated or too labor-intensive to harvest content from.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] The pages being scraped may embrace metadata or semantic markups and annotations, which can be used to locate specific data snippets.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] If the annotations are embedded in the pages, as Microformat does, this technique can be viewed as a special case of DOM parsing.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] In another case, the annotations, organized into a semantic layer, are stored and managed separately from the web pages, so the scrapers can retrieve data schema and instructions from this layer before scraping the pages.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] There are efforts using machine learning and computer vision that attempt to identify and extract information from web pages by interpreting pages visually as a human being might.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] The legality of web scraping varies across the world.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] In general, web scraping may be against the terms of service of some websites, but the enforceability of these terms is unclear.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] In the United States, website owners can use three major legal claims to prevent undesired web scraping: (1) copyright infringement (compilation), (2) violation of the Computer Fraud and Abuse Act ("CFAA"), and (3) trespass to chattel.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] However, the effectiveness of these claims relies upon meeting various criteria, and the case law is still evolving.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] For example, with regard to copyright, while outright duplication of original expression will in many cases be illegal, in the United States the courts ruled in *Feist Publications v.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] Rural Telephone Service* that duplication of facts is allowable.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] U.S. courts have acknowledged that users of "scrapers" or "robots" may be held liable for committing trespass to chattels, which involves a computer system itself being considered personal property upon which the user of a scraper is trespassing.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] Bidder's Edge*, resulted in an injunction ordering Bidder's Edge to stop accessing, collecting, and indexing auctions from the eBay web site.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] This case involved automatic placing of bids, known as auction sniping.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] Not all cases of web spidering brought before the courts have been considered trespass to chattels.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] One of the first major tests of screen scraping involved American Airlines (AA), and a firm called FareChase.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] AA successfully obtained an injunction from a Texas trial court, stopping FareChase from selling software that enables users to compare online fares if the software also searches AA's website.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] The airline argued that FareChase's websearch software trespassed on AA's servers when it collected the publicly available data.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] FareChase filed an appeal in March 2003.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] By June, FareChase and AA agreed to settle and the appeal was dropped.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] Southwest Airlines has also challenged screen-scraping practices, and has involved both FareChase and another firm, Outtask, in a legal claim.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] Southwest Airlines charged that the screen-scraping is Illegal since it is an example of "Computer Fraud and Abuse" and has led to "Damage and Loss" and "Unauthorized Access" of Southwest's site.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] It also constitutes "Interference with Business Relations", "Trespass", and "Harmful Access by Computer".
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] They also claimed that screen-scraping constitutes what is legally known as "Misappropriation and Unjust Enrichment", as well as being a breach of the web site's user agreement.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] Outtask denied all these claims, claiming that the prevailing law, in this case, should be US Copyright law and that under copyright, the pieces of information being scraped would not be subject to copyright protection.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] Although the cases were never resolved in the Supreme Court of the United States, FareChase was eventually shuttered by parent company Yahoo!, and Outtask was purchased by travel expense company Concur.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] In 2012, a startup called 3Taps scraped classified housing ads from Craigslist.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] Craigslist sent 3Taps a cease-and-desist letter and blocked their IP addresses and later sued, in *Craigslist v.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] The court held that the cease-and-desist letter and IP blocking was sufficient for Craigslist to properly claim that 3Taps had violated the Computer Fraud and Abuse Act (CFAA).
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] Although these are early scraping decisions, and the theories of liability are not uniform, it is difficult to ignore a pattern emerging that the courts are prepared to protect proprietary content on commercial sites from uses which are undesirable to the owners of such sites.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] While the law in this area becomes more settled, entities contemplating using scraping programs to access a public web site should also consider whether such action is authorized by reviewing the terms of use and other terms or notices posted on or made available through the site.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] Eventbrite Inc.* (2010), the United States district court for the eastern district of Virginia, ruled that the terms of use should be brought to the users' attention in order for a browsewrap contract or license to be enforceable.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] In a 2014 case, filed in the United States District Court for the Eastern District of Pennsylvania, e-commerce site QVC objected to the Pinterest-like shopping aggregator Resultly's 'scraping of QVC's site for real-time pricing data.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] QVC alleges that Resultly "excessively crawled" QVC's retail site (allegedly sending 200-300 search requests to QVC's website per minute, sometimes to up to 36,000 requests per minute) which caused QVC's site to crash for two days, resulting in lost sales for QVC.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] QVC's complaint alleges that the defendant disguised its web crawler to mask its source IP address and thus prevented QVC from quickly repairing the problem.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] This is a particularly interesting scraping case because QVC is seeking damages for the unavailability of their website, which QVC claims was caused by Resultly.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] In the plaintiff's web site during the period of this trial, the terms of use link are displayed among all the links of the site, at the bottom of the page as most sites on the internet.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] This ruling contradicts the Irish ruling described below.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] The court also rejected the plaintiff's argument that the browse-wrap restrictions were enforceable in view of Virginia's adoption of the Uniform Computer Information Transactions Act (UCITA)—a uniform law that many believed was in favor on common browse-wrap contracting practices.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] Power Ventures, Inc.*, a district court ruled in 2012 that Power Ventures could not scrape Facebook pages on behalf of a Facebook user.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] The case is on appeal, and the Electronic Frontier Foundation filed a brief in 2015 asking that it be overturned.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] Holdings, Inc.*, a court in the US held Meltwater liable for scraping and republishing news information from the Associated Press, but a court in the United Kingdom held in favor of Meltwater.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] The Ninth Circuit ruled in 2019 that web scraping did not violate the CFAA in *hiQ Labs v.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] The case was appealed to the United States Supreme Court, which returned the case to the Ninth Circuit to reconsider the case in light of the 2021 Supreme Court decision in *Van Buren v.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] United States* which narrowed the applicability of the CFAA.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] On this review, the Ninth Circuit upheld their prior decision.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] Internet Archive collects and distributes a significant number of publicly available web pages without being considered to be in violation of copyright laws.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] In February 2006, the Danish Maritime and Commercial Court (Copenhagen) ruled that systematic crawling, indexing, and deep linking by portal site ofir.dk of real estate site Home.dk does not conflict with Danish law or the database directive of the European Union.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] Ethical data scraping supports offmarket sourcing in business but must comply with GDPR to avoid privacy violations in automated data collection.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] In a February 2010 case complicated by matters of jurisdiction, Ireland's High Court delivered a verdict that illustrates the inchoate state of developing case law.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] In the case of *Ryanair Ltd v Billigfluege.de GmbH*, Ireland's High Court ruled Ryanair's "click-wrap" agreement to be legally binding.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] The decision is under appeal in Ireland's Supreme Court.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] On April 30, 2020, the French Data Protection Authority (CNIL) released new guidelines on web scraping.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] The CNIL guidelines made it clear that publicly available data is still personal data and cannot be repurposed without the knowledge of the person to whom that data belongs.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] In Australia, the Spam Act 2003 outlaws some forms of web harvesting, although this only applies to email addresses.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] Besides a few cases dealing with IPR infringement, Indian courts have not expressly ruled on the legality of web scraping.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] However, since all common forms of electronic contracts are enforceable in India, violating the terms of use prohibiting data scraping will be a violation of the contract law.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] It will also violate the Information Technology Act, 2000, which penalizes unauthorized access to a computer resource or extracting data from a computer resource.
[src:bot-management/web-scraping] The administrator of a website can use various measures to stop or slow a bot.
